The paper deals with the problem of distributed function computation, which involves encoding and decoding of data in a distributed manner. This problem is closely related to distributed source coding (DSC), which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of an interactive communication protocol for computing the worst-case achievable rate-region for any function, which involves the use of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also mentions the optimization of the number of informant bits required, which is a problem in computational complexity (cs.CC). The asymmetric communication scenarios mentioned in the paper involve correlated informants, which is a topic in social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of minimizing the number of informant bits required, which is a problem in network information theory (cs.NI).
